[SPEAKER_00] We actually liked what we learned after World War II, that peace was much better than war.

365
00:31:07,940 --> 00:31:10,000
[SPEAKER_00] We like being a union.

366
00:31:10,000 --> 00:31:17,039
[SPEAKER_00] We like having a European Green Deal because that inspires the whole rest of the world to get on with sustainability.

367
00:31:17,039 --> 00:31:21,019
[SPEAKER_00] If Europe did that, it would be safe.

368
00:31:21,019 --> 00:31:22,740
[SPEAKER_00] It would be admired.

369
00:31:22,740 --> 00:31:28,299
[SPEAKER_00] It would be visited, as it is, of course, by everybody in the world because everybody loves Europe.

370
00:31:28,299 --> 00:31:34,759
[SPEAKER_00] That's what Europe should be doing, not becoming an appendage of NATO, for God's sake.

371
00:31:34,759 --> 00:31:36,079
[SPEAKER_00] The U.S. is a little crazy.

372
00:31:36,079 --> 00:31:38,460
[SPEAKER_00] The U.S. wants to run the world.

373
00:31:38,460 --> 00:31:40,200
[SPEAKER_00] Europe doesn't need to run the world.

374
00:31:40,200 --> 00:31:49,180
[SPEAKER_00] Europe needs to run Europe, be happy, and inspire other places to have peace and an internal union.

375
00:31:49,180 --> 00:31:57,940
[SPEAKER_00] And by the way, there was every prospect for good relations between Europe and Russia all along.

376
00:31:57,940 --> 00:32:01,420
[SPEAKER_00] I was Gorbachev's economic advisor, one of them.

377
00:32:01,579 --> 00:32:03,619
[SPEAKER_00] I was Yeltsin's economic advisor.

378
00:32:03,619 --> 00:32:10,539
[SPEAKER_00] I know they wanted peace, a common European home, trade.

379
00:32:10,539 --> 00:32:15,839
[SPEAKER_00] They wanted to catch up after decades of a terrible system that they had.

380
00:32:15,839 --> 00:32:20,319
[SPEAKER_00] They didn't want renewed war, for God's sake.

381
00:32:20,319 --> 00:32:22,160
[SPEAKER_00] They didn't want to invade Europe.

382
00:32:22,160 --> 00:32:22,960
[SPEAKER_00] It was crazy.

383
00:32:23,619 --> 00:32:29,660
[SPEAKER_00] We should have disbanded NATO back in 1991 when the Warsaw Pact was disbanded.

384
00:32:29,660 --> 00:32:31,259
[SPEAKER_00] Everyone could live at peace.

385
00:32:31,259 --> 00:32:38,759
[SPEAKER_00] But no, the United States had to decide immediately, ah, now we go on to dismantle Russia, too.

386
00:32:39,000 --> 00:32:41,000
[SPEAKER_00] Because the U.S. wants domination.

387
00:32:41,000 --> 00:32:42,119
[SPEAKER_00] It didn't want peace.

388
00:32:42,119 --> 00:32:43,799
[SPEAKER_00] It wants dominance.

389
00:32:43,799 --> 00:32:51,980
[SPEAKER_00] Now, again, it's an old-fashioned, old, outmoded, anachronistic, and very dangerous idea.

390
00:32:51,980 --> 00:32:54,180
[SPEAKER_00] So we need a new foreign policy.

391
00:32:54,180 --> 00:32:55,819
[SPEAKER_00] But you asked me, could peace come?

392
00:32:55,819 --> 00:33:01,240
[SPEAKER_00] It could come instantaneously if the United States would adopt a more realistic view.

393
00:33:02,240 --> 00:33:04,819
[SPEAKER_01] Okay, and now for my final question.

394
00:33:04,819 --> 00:33:10,440
[SPEAKER_01] The Croatian government has so far given about 300 million euros in aid to Ukraine.

395
00:33:10,440 --> 00:33:19,420
[SPEAKER_01] At the same time, Croatian pensioners receive an average pension of around 350 euros for 40 years of work.

396
00:33:19,420 --> 00:33:20,759
[SPEAKER_01] How do you comment this?

397
00:33:20,759 --> 00:33:24,119
[SPEAKER_00] Look, get together with your neighbors.

398
00:33:24,119 --> 00:33:29,440
[SPEAKER_00] Get together with Viktor Orban, with Roberto Fizzo.

399
00:33:29,900 --> 00:33:34,660
[SPEAKER_00] Get together with all the people who are winning the elections, actually, across Europe.

400
00:33:34,660 --> 00:33:39,440
[SPEAKER_00] Because the ones that are winning the elections are the ones, they call them right-wing.

401
00:33:39,440 --> 00:33:45,099
[SPEAKER_00] But the truth is, the ones that are winning the elections are the ones that say, we don't like this war.

402
00:33:45,099 --> 00:33:47,259
[SPEAKER_00] We want to get back to peace.

403
00:33:47,259 --> 00:33:53,539
[SPEAKER_00] And so this is really what Croatia should do.

404
00:33:53,539 --> 00:33:57,519
[SPEAKER_00] War is expensive, and it's very dangerous.

405
00:33:58,140 --> 00:34:07,119
[SPEAKER_00] And Croatia, like everyone else, would benefit from Russian tourists and benefit from nice relations with Russia and all the rest.

406
00:34:07,119 --> 00:34:08,920
[SPEAKER_00] They've got money to spend.

407
00:34:08,920 --> 00:34:13,179
[SPEAKER_00] Croatia has some of the most beautiful places in the whole planet.

408
00:34:13,179 --> 00:34:16,820
[SPEAKER_00] And so this should be a peaceful country.

409
00:34:17,320 --> 00:34:26,559
[SPEAKER_00] Don't get caught up in this crazy spiral of violence and rhetoric and hatred.

410
00:34:26,559 --> 00:34:29,119
[SPEAKER_00] There's no basis for it.

411
00:34:29,119 --> 00:34:32,440
[SPEAKER_00] There's no basis for what's going on.

412
00:34:32,440 --> 00:34:36,219
[SPEAKER_00] Russia does not need or want more land.

413
00:34:36,219 --> 00:34:41,699
[SPEAKER_00] It wants the United States to respect it and to not threaten its security.

414
00:34:42,159 --> 00:34:43,539
[SPEAKER_00] This is what Russia wants.

415
00:34:43,539 --> 00:34:51,019
[SPEAKER_00] And Russia should get that because, as an American, it's not doing me one whit of good.

416
00:34:51,019 --> 00:34:56,280
[SPEAKER_00] It's only making my life more dangerous when NATO tries to expand.

417
00:34:56,280 --> 00:35:03,280
[SPEAKER_00] I'm sick of it, too, because it just puts me under a nuclear risk that I don't want to be under.

418
00:35:03,559 --> 00:35:06,480
[SPEAKER_00] That's the only risk, by the way, the United States faces.

419
00:35:06,480 --> 00:35:08,500
[SPEAKER_00] No one's going to invade the United States.

420
00:35:08,500 --> 00:35:11,440
[SPEAKER_00] No one's going to attack the United States.

421
00:35:11,440 --> 00:35:17,420
[SPEAKER_00] The only single security risk of the United States conceivable as a nuclear war.

422
00:35:17,539 --> 00:35:25,500
[SPEAKER_00] So if they had a whit of sense about them, that's what they'd be trying to avoid, rather than saying, oh, Putin's we should call his bluff.

423
00:35:25,500 --> 00:35:26,820
[SPEAKER_00] He's just bluffing.

424
00:35:26,820 --> 00:35:34,139
[SPEAKER_00] All these idiots, you know, want to provoke to the point that, oh, sorry, we made a mistake, at which point the world's over.

425
00:35:34,139 --> 00:35:37,179
[SPEAKER_00] So this is my advice to Croatia.

426
00:35:37,179 --> 00:35:39,880
[SPEAKER_00] You have plenty of neighbors that figure this out.

427
00:35:39,880 --> 00:35:41,179
[SPEAKER_00] Figure it out, too.

428
00:35:41,179 --> 00:35:42,980
[SPEAKER_00] Everybody should get together.

429
00:35:43,480 --> 00:35:57,460
[SPEAKER_00] By the way, even Petr Pavel in the Czech Republic, who has been NATO, pro-NATO, pro-NATO, recently said realistically, you know, Ukraine cannot win this war.

430
00:35:57,460 --> 00:36:01,300
[SPEAKER_00] So there's more common sense coming in the neighborhood now.

431
00:36:01,300 --> 00:36:05,860
[SPEAKER_00] Get together with the people of common sense and tell the Americans some truth.

432
00:36:05,860 --> 00:36:07,300
[SPEAKER_01] Great.

433
00:36:07,300 --> 00:36:10,699
[SPEAKER_01] Professor Sachs, thank you very much for this interview.

434
00:36:10,699 --> 00:36:12,039
[SPEAKER_00] Great to be with you.

435
00:36:12,039 --> 00:36:12,820
[SPEAKER_00] I appreciate it.

436
00:36:12,820 --> 00:36:14,179
[SPEAKER_01] Thank you once again.

437
00:36:14,179 --> 00:36:15,559
